column1: Between 15 February 2019 and 31 October 2019, which company from among Alphabet, Amazon, Apple, and Microsoft will first reach an end-of-day  market capitalization of $1 trillion?
column6: ['Finance', 'Technology']
Based in @Emil report.
It's over. MSFT closed above 130.5. When Bloomberg update their market cap it should show that it is just over 1T.

The competition is between Microsoft and Apple. Apple reports Q1 results after market today. If Microsoft doesn't reach 1 trillion at EOD, there's still possibility that Apple can have an upward surprise.
Alphabet misses earnings, stock plummets

Update: Microsoft's stocks has been on the rise due to the success of their clouding software. Their recent gains has been larger than expected and they a market cap of 994.404B (30.4.19), they are currently doing significantly better than Apple, and could be the first to hit the 1 Trillion dollars market cap. (https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-24/microsoft-profit-sales-top-estimates-amid-flurry-of-cloud-wins)

Amazon stock hasn't moved much since their earnings announcement last week. So I'm reducing its chances and putting those chips on Microsoft. MSFT is only a hair below $1T, so it amazes me that the crowd only puts the odds at 29%. Anything could happen, but the odds strongly favor Microsoft at this point.

Maybe this isn't fair enough, but according to CNBC on April 25, Microsoft first hits $1 trillion market cap for the first time as stock jumps on earnings best. It jumped about 5.1% which pushing the company past the trillion value on a “better-than-expected” earnings report. Besides Microsoft, Apple and Amazon are tied at the second tier. Something worth to know is that both "A" companies have hit the trillion cap in 2018 respectively. Apple was on August 2, 2018, and Amazon was on September 4 the same year after Apple.

(29/04/2019) N.B. As Bloomberg recently argued talking about Microsoft, "The company’s shares rose as much as 5.1 per cent Thursday morning in New York, briefly pushing its valuation across US$1 trillion before pulling back slightly. The move nosed the software maker ahead of Apple Inc. as the world’s most valuable company. The two tech giants, along with Amazon.com Inc., are all within striking distance of the symbolic US$1 trillion mark as their stocks have rallied this year." (https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/microsoft-poised-to-top-us-1-trillion-in-value-beating-amazon-and-apple-1.1249298). The company's evaluation is not the same as market capitalization - many websites claim that Microsoft already reached the trillion, which is not - but Microsoft's trillionaire aim seems near. Nevertheless, I still remain cautions for eventual drastic drops.

Seeing as Microsoft is ahead of Apple and Amazon by so much it is at this point unrealistic to assume that they will pass the 1 trillion mark first, therefore Microsoft gets the highest percentage. Apple and Amazon get the same percentage as they have relatively similar market capitalization at this point (April 29th).

Apparently Microsoft is doing great (today, 28 April 2019, the market capitalization is 995.323B). Alphabet seems to still be out of the games, while Amazon and Apple are at around 960B. At this point Microsoft, if it doesn't have to face a serious and immediate backdrop in the very next days, is going to reach the trillion fairly soon.
MS at $995. C’mon - baby needs a new pair of shoes!

Due to my limited expertise regarding market capitalization, as well as tech companies, the forecast at hand seeks its point of departure in recent market capitalization development data of Alphabet, Amazon, Apple and Microsoft, as well as estimations and reasonings made by corresponding journals.
I am assuming that big moves ahead of April 30 earnings for Apple are unlikely so I am lowering it compared to Amazon and MSFT relative to the results of my model.

AMZN announced fantastic earnings, but the stock isn't moving much. AAPL has stopped moving up; maybe investors are waiting for the upcoming earnings announcement. Google (Alphabet) is nowhere near $1T, but somehow still is being given an 11% chance of finishing first. This demonstrates that for some challenges it is insufficient to review predictions only once a week. [I've been guilty of going longer than that at times. Sometimes there just isn't the time.]

Disclaimer: I’m not enough expert about economy to answer this question relying on precise mathematical formulas, market analysis or economic relations between different data (for instance the exact relations between growth rate and market cap). My fear is leaving out too many data or focusing too much on some of them, chosen randomly. Such a procedure would be incomplete and erroneous. I don’t want to work too much with number if I’m not enough confident on them, because there is the risk of simplifying the calculation, overlooking information, and reaching an inconsistent outcome, very hard to consider as valuable. So, I will start my analysis using numbers but just to have an overview of the current and recent situation of the companies, then I will focus on some more discursive argumentations. However, I’ll show how the differences between the companies are sometimes very subtle and is difficult to make predictions.
Today, 26th April, the market capitalization of the 4 companies is as follows:
Amazon q1
Based on today's performance.
Despite the deluge of false headlines, MSFT has yet to secure $1T. AMZN still well short after this afternoon's modest earnings rise. Can AAPL make it 3 more trading days, to an earnings boosted win?

MSFT didn't manage to close above 1T but at 990 so I ran my model again. Latest probabilities are approximately: 0, 7, 20, 73, 0. However, I am adjusting toward MSFT given its strong earnings and the seemingly positive market sentiment toward it.

MSFT is very close to the $1T mark, but it doesn't look like it will hit it today. That leaves open the possibility that AMZN will pop after earnings are announced after the close. If AMZN fades it will be a race between AAPL and MSFT. That provides an interesting finish for this challenge. I'm favoring MSFT due to its momentum and its valuation, which is less than one percentage point away from $1T.
MS is up APPL is down.
MSFT has passed the $1T mark. If it hold until the end of the day this challenge will be over.
Microsoft passed 1T in after hour trading after it beat earnings expectations. https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/24/microsoft-q3-2019-earnings.html

Microsoft briefly passed $1T in after-hours trading, apparently during or after an analyst conference call. Everything will depend on follow through in trading tomorrow. Based on this information it seems that MSFT may pass the finish line before Apple or Amazon announce their earnings. So I'm shifting from favoring AAPL to win this challenge to favoring Microsoft.

MSFT announced good earnings and revenue growth after the close today, and the stock is up 2.5% after hours. Those gains could fade tomorrow, or the stock could continue higher. The follow through as the market digests the news over the next few days could move Microsoft over the finish line before Apple announces earnings on April 30. And Amazon will announce Q1 earnings tomorrow (April 25).
This is all about the data
playing it safe for now because for some reason I can't get into the Bloomberg site

MSFT reports earnings after the market close today. The stock is about 3.9% short of $1T. I'm betting that even a pretty good announcement will cause a 2-2.5% pop, not quite enough. And sometimes with great news a stock will actually fall, per the old saw that says "buy on the rumor, sell on the news." I have no idea what they will announce.

Update: Yesterday's end-of-day market cap for the companies in question are listed below. Next to each the growth rates since my last forecast, the 7th of April (7th to 23rd, then), are recorded: Amazon: 928.657, 2.9% Alphabet: 883.496, 5.11% Apple: 964.416, 3.82% Microsoft: 961.559, 4.54%
Based on latest model [1] results.

AAPL and MSFT are closing in on $1T -- at this rate this challenge will be over within a week. Anything could happen if there are announcements from the companies. But Apple only needs to advance another 7-8 points to reach the finish line. Microsoft isn't far behind. I don't quite understand why the crowd gives AMZN a better chance to win than MSFT, or why Alphabet still gets an 8% chance. Alphabet is WAY behind as the others approach $1T.
When will this madness end?
Per my latest QuickValue + TickerTruth read, looks like a done deal for Apple: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/13Kbp26mLtpDRwdUct65_YLuvS77xADLj_ylUoQuFLMY/edit?usp=drivesdk

Amazon with its brand and diversity of business sources can trade positively in the short term news cycle and drive valuations above $1T. A simple announcement of something innovative in Whole Foods, Prime, or any of its services can cause a trading surge. Apple on the hand has the most to gain from multiples and can also reach the $1T mark, providing it resolves its market share issues in China. Alphabet has the farthest to go and is behind Amazon and Apple by approx. $100m in market cap. Microsoft valuations seems a bit frothy despite it being a legacy tech name.
Current market capitalization 22/04/19, ranked:

Apple is the closest to the $1T level -- a 4% increase will do it. But a good announcement could cause a large enough pop to put any one of the top three over the line very quickly. I'm following the numbers, which say that Apple has the best chance to get there first.

most of these valuations are unwarranted given global outlook. Regardless, bumped up Apple and Microsoft. “Sell in May and walk away” may be outdated but suspect “headwinds” and some of the companies I work with are preparing to keep their powder dry for another day...

In my previous forecast, my bet was on the possibility of no company reaching the trillion. Given the last month's market development, I need to edit this consideration - unfortunately, as previously stated, economics is not my field. Roughly overlooking the market development over the month and the year of each company, Alphabet seems the most unlikely to reach the trillion. In the moment in which I write, Apple and Microsoft seems the most likely, but I think Microsoft's growth will soon meet a low market performance. My candidates remain Apple and Amazon, but apparently my faith in Amazaon has not been repain in market capitalization - at the moment, Apple is fairly close to the trillion, with 961.257B. Given these intakes, I drastically changed my forecast, following the market's history which remembers that Apple was the first reaching the trillion, and seems to be the most likely to reach it again.
Amazon business can grow 'every day'. There is no limit, I believe.

- goog doesn't have the daily liquidity to surpass amazon or apple - aaple and msft have best (highest) liquidity or # of shares traded daily and apple is closest to 1 trillion market cap - amazon has the best increase from YTD lowest point (46% increase from low of $1344 to today's price of $1861 followed by aapl 43% MSFT has good volume and a lot of current interest, and closer to 1 trillion market cap than amzn but not as close as aapl -Aapl has a more volatile chart than amzn, which is upward and flat, and a lot more volume (like a million times more) so a good market day probably would tip aaple past 1 trillion first

To predict which of the above companies that will first reach a market capitalization of 1 trillion dollars, it is beneficial to look at their past growth rates. As a general trend, the stock market, and thereby the market capitalizations, did extremely poorly in December of 2018. All of the companies have experienced overall growth since then. Alphabet Current MC: 860.33B Average daily growth rate from Jan. 1st - April 18th 2019: 1.21% Days to 1 trillion dollars: 116 days, August 12th 2019. Amazon Current MC: 917.18B Average daily growth rate from Jan. 1st – April 18th 2019: 1.46% Days to 1 trillion dollars: 58 days, June 22nd 2019. Apple Current MC: 960. 31B Average daily growth rate from Jan. 1st – April 18th 2019: 1.95% Days to 1 trillion dollars: 20 days, May 8th 2019. Microsoft Current MC: 942.15B Average daily growth rate from Jan 1st – April 18th 2019: 1.54 % Days to 1 trillion dollars: 35 days, May 23rd 2019.
according to Bloomberg MS's growth rate is nearly double Apple's.

Apple is within 6% of $1T. I'm increasing the chances for AAPL to 37%. But MSFT and AMZN still could get there first with a sprint after a good announcement.

Apple and Amazon both reached the symbolic level in 2018, but have both fallen below it since. This fall is due particularly to the sell-offs U.S. stocks endured in the fourth quarter of 2018. In those three months, Apple’s stock lost 30 percent of its value, Amazon’s shed 25 percent, Alphabet’s fell 13 percent and Microsoft’s sank 11 percent Source : https://www.cnbc.com/2019/01/10/cramer-tracks-race-back-to-1-trillion-amazon-leads-apple-lags.html).
This forecast is based primarily on historical data, and solved mathematically. It does not feign the ability to understand or project future market fluctuations.
From the April 5 closing prices the required increases for each of the four to reach $1T (according to Bloomberg.com) are as follows:

Unfortunately, the only thing here I can assess for sure is that I have 0 knowledge both in Tech companies and in market capitalization. Given this little disclaimer, here is what I believe after some research:

a. Based on the current market cap (as at end of April 3rd), Apple and Microsoft's position is about 9% away from 1 trillion, while alphabet and amazon are about 20% away. b. Based on historical data: 1. Analyzing a one year period, all of the four companies have potential to reach 1 trillion based on historical % increase. 2. Analyzing short term, a two week analysis showing every company decreased in market cap, a one month analysis showed that Apple had a 11% increase, higher than the 9% required. Microsoft is a close 6% one month actual vs. 9% required.

Assumptions: * Both Apple and Amazon have reached the 1 trillion border before, but have dropped down well below the mark since. * Currently Apple and Microsoft are above 900 billion mark and Amazon and Alphabet are below that mark. * Growth rates in recent 2 years of market capitalization have become more volatile than before. * 7 months left before closing the question

Updated my model to incorporate correlation with S&P500. New results give much higher probability of AMZN hitting a trillion first. This makes sense as it's the riskiest asset with 20% more variability than the next riskiest which is AAPL.

I pulled return data for each security on a rolling 7-month basis (time from today until deadline) back 20 years and calculated the historical probability of each of the securities achieving returns sufficient to bring their market cap above $1 trillion, then calculated the joint probabilities of all sets of outcomes (alphabet alone, alphabet AND amazon, Apple and Microsoft and Amazon, etc) and generated a range of outcomes for each security as well as the joint probability that none would achieve $1T by October 31. I will update monthly as we get closer. Huge caveat being that past performance is not necessarily an indicator of future events and where the companies are currently. This is purely a backward-looking outcome and if returns are a random walk may likely be useless :)
https://seekingalpha.com/news/3445445-apple-launches-news-channels-tv?ifp=0

I have to admit I don't really know anything about how to estimate a comany's end-of-day market capitalization. Given the fact that any kind of market study, estimation over the actions' value, and analysis over the growth of a comany would be not only terribly wrong, but also offensive in regards to the experts and students of the subject, I have to try to do this forecast anyway, hoping that Tetlock's right and non experts tend to do better forecasts rather than experts. The only indicator I could possibly express my opinion about in this regard is the potential of a company from now to the end of october. To understand this, I made a naive research about these companies' new products, and I tried to immagine their impact on their actual end-of-day market capitalization. First of all, I had to understand what alphabet is - as already stated, my ignorance in the matter is deep, but if even for you it's the first time hearing about alphabet, here's some help (https://www.lifewire.com/understanding-google-and-alphabet-4116085). Alphabet seems indeed a promising enterprise, Cramer is absolutely crazy about it, and recently they announced "Backstory, a cybersecurity product designed to help companies figure out how to protect themselves from hackers." (https://www.businessinsider.com/alphabet-chronicle-backstory-splunk-2019-3?r=US&IR=T&IR=T). Then we have Amazon, which, together with Apple, already hit the trillion, and whose program in innovation is pretty outstanding (https://www.aboutamazon.com/innovation). Apple seems on the verge to annouce some new products, such as the new MacBook Pro, a MacBook Air, a new IPad and IPhone XI (https://www.techradar.com/news/the-big-three-in-2019-apple-google-and-microsofts-upcoming-hardware-year). If I understood things correctly, Google's performace can help Alphabet, and a new Google assistant system seems to be on the way (https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/10/18175524/google-assistant-devices-ces-2019-tvs-soundbars-smart-speakers-kitchen-bathroom-cars). Finally, Microsoft may release the new Surface Book 3, maybe a new XBox, the Surface Pro 7 and Surface Phone. That said, the forecast is just about what I think is going to have more effect on the market. Right now Microsoft is leading, followed by Apple, Amazon and Alphabet. Nevertheless, I think it's still not Alphabet's time to beat Apple and Amazon. Moreover, I think Apple's and Amazon's innovations can have a stronger impact - and consider that new products can be ordered and delivered by Amazon itself, through its new innovative delivery and packaging systems. Hence, if one of the companies will reach the trillion, I think it will be Amazon, even though Apple stands absolutely a chance. That said, I think the most likely outcome will be that none of the companies will reach the trillion by the end of october. I don't even know how to explain it, I will just say that every company is more than 100 billions away from the trillion, and I don't think they'll be able to reach that result before november.

Over the next 25 years, 87% of voters believe Facebook will have to deal with significant competition that will challenge its dominance. A ScottRasmussen.com poll found that 52% believe it is likely that the social media giant will actually go out of business during that time.

Oops! I've overlooked AMZN. Its recent 100 point increase puts it within 12% of the $1T mark. It needs to reach $2000/share, a level it already reached last September. With three contenders I'll further decrease the chances for "NOTA," while bumping up the odds for AMZN.

The yield curve has inverted, and the markets are off quite a bit on the news. Typically it takes 2-3 years for a recession to begin after an inversion. There is a good chance the equity markets will recover within a few days or weeks. A China trade deal, even a mediocre one, could get the market moving higher again. Likewise a resolution on Brexit, even a bad one, will remove an uncertainty.

Latest results from Random Walk model. The latest guidance by the Fed lowers the chances of "None of the above" and I am sticking with the results from the model rather than adjusting None of the Above higher.

Microsoft now only 9.7% away, with ~154 trading days to go. Over last 4 years, ~74% of ROC(154) periods cleared this threshold. Amazon 13.6% away, ~73% cleared. Apple 8.2% away, ~59% cleared. Alphabet 16.5% away, ~32% cleared. Paradoxically, however, relative strength is inverted: GOOGL > AAPL > AMZN > MSFT.

Amazon has been growing faster than the US GDP and continues to enter different industries such as grocery stores and cleaning services. While Apple is launching the next generation of Airpods in the coming months, the iPhone XR sales were lower than projected and the next generation iPhone is unlikely to be too different from the popular iPhone X. Microsoft is a mature stable company and it is unlikely to launch groundbreaking products. Alphabet is not growing as fast as Amazon, so I see Amazon reaching the $1 trillion market cap before Alphabet and Apple.
Apple and Microsoft are both within about 15% of the magic number. I've put the probability at >50% that one of them will breach $1T.
Potential (likely) resolution of the trade dispute with China [1] lowers the likelihood of "None of the above".

Microsoft has to move up less than 14% to get to $1T, and its trajectory is up. Likewise Apple is moving up lately, and it has the lowest valuation of the group. And Apple has already been at $1T. Amazon has also been at $1T. But it has the furthest to go, so I've put it in third place. Still the favorite is "not of the above" at 47%.
With Pocahontas beating the drum to break these companies up and headwinds in USA economy, unlikely any will see the increases required to breach $1 trillion (again in some cases)

When there is a big slowdown in earnings growth, as we are experiencing, the best-performing sectors are usually defensive stocks like consumer staples, not tech. In this environment it would be a surprise for tech to post the required gains of 20% or so in a matter of a year, let alone doing so in a few months.

Microsoft, Amazon, and Apple are all doing well and close to each other at $851B, $815B, and $801B respectively. That being said, Apple usually only shoots up after big product launches so I think they are unlikely to be first. Microsoft has been going up lately and, while it is dangerous to presume future activity based on past performance, I think they are in a good position to keep growing. Amazon of course just keeps growing and growing and may easily be lifted up in a general stock market rally.

Taking @Emil 's random walk calculcation as the baseline: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/827344

I took the outside view by using historical average daily change and standard deviations to build random walks. I repeated the walks 5k times and the my algorithm recorded how many times a company reached 1 trillion.
